[1]
Date: Sun 26 Jun 2005
From: Dan Silver <dsilver@reedpointgroup.com>
Source: Kyodo News, 26 Jun 2005 [edited]
<http://home.kyodo.co.jp/modules/fstStory/index.php?storyid=3D188555>


Bird flu virus found at Ibaraki farm that had mass chicken deaths
-----------------------------------------------------------------
A weak strain of the H5N2 type avian influenza virus has been detected in
chickens at a poultry farm in Mitsukaido, Ibaraki Prefecture, where about
800 of its 25 000 chickens died between April and June 2005, the Ministry
of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries said on Sunday [26 Jun 2005].

The ministry announced a ban on transporting chickens and eggs from within
a 5 km radius from the farm to places outside of the area to prevent any
possible spread of the virus, although prefectural officials who checked
the site and nearby farms on Saturday [25 Jun 2005] found no further
abnormalities.

On Monday [27 Jun 2005], the authorities will begin culling all of 25 000
chickens currently kept at the infected farm and disinfecting the site. The
H5N2 type is a weak strain of the bird flu virus, compared with the more
deadly H5N1 type that hit Japan in 3 outbreaks last year in Yamaguchi, Oita
and Kyoto prefectures.

The farm reported the case to the Ibaraki prefectural authorities on Friday
[24 Jun 2005] after a simple test conducted by a private organization at
the farm's request turned out positive results for the virus. The infection
was confirmed by the National Institution of Animal Health by Sunday.
Currently, the number of eggs laid by chickens at the farm has recovered to
normal, and there have been no more mass deaths of the birds. Eggs from the
infected farm have been shipped to the market through distributors in
Saitama Prefecture and retailers in Tokyo.

--
Dan Silver
<dsilver@reedpointgroup.com>

[Typically, avian influenza of low pathogenicity may be, at times,
clinically expressed by an ephemeral drop in egg production without further
noticeable symptoms. Such cases may escape immediate diagnosis to be
detected later by serological examinations. - Mod.AS]

