[2]
Date: Sun 26 Jun 2005
From: Mary Marshall <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Reuters alert news, 26 Jun 2005 [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/T83303.htm>


Bird flu virus found in chicken in eastern Japan
------------------------------------------------
A type of bird flu virus has been detected at a chicken farm in eastern
Japan where hundreds of fowl died earlier this year [2005], a Japanese Farm
Ministry spokesman said on Sunday [26 Jun 2005].

The virus that was detected was a "weak" form of bird flu, the spokesman
said. Kyodo news agency said the strain identified was "H5N2", which is
less virulent than the "H5N1" strain found in previous avian flu outbreaks
in Japan.

The H5N1 virus has killed dozens of people in Asia since 2003, while
millions of birds have been slaughtered to contain the disease. Around 430
chickens died between March and May [2005] at a chicken farm in Ibaraki
prefecture, an official for the Ibaraki prefectural government said earlier.

The Farm Ministry plans to limit the movement of eggs and chickens in a 5
km (3 mile) radius around the chicken farm to prevent the virus from
spreading, Kyodo said.

Local officials inspected the farm on Saturday [25 Jun 2005], but found "no
particular irregularities" among chickens, the Ibaraki official said,
adding that the incident was reported to local officials on Friday. Japan
suffered several outbreaks of bird flu last year [2004], including an
outbreak in Kyoto in western Japan in February.

After the February 2004 outbreak, some 240 000 chickens and 20 million eggs
were disposed of at the Kyoto farm and another one nearby to prevent the
disease from spreading.

--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[This case of H5N2, though -- probably -- of low pathogenicity, should be
notified to the Office International des Epizooties in line with Article
2.7.12.5. of the Terrestrial Animal Health Code. According to the said
(revised) article, a Notifiable avian influenza (NAI) is defined as an
infection of poultry caused by any influenza A virus of the H5 or H7
subtypes. An NAI can be subdivided into 2 categories related to its
pathogenicity for chickens, being either high (HPNAI) or low (LPNAI), as
defined by prescribed criteria.

A low pathogenic H5N2 avian influenza virus was detected on 2 farms in
Taiwan during January 2004. The outbreak was promptly eradicated by the
application of stamping-out policy without vaccination. According to their
follow-up report to the OIE, an extensive targeted surveillance did not
detect any evidence of the virus since 9 Mar 2004. - Mod.AS]
